findings.description:
RepoConfig.ts has 28 section-banner dividers — the highest count in the codebase. runDirectoryManager.ts, Feature.ts, traces.ts, and rateLimitLedger.ts each have 12-20 banners. These dividers appear every 30-50 lines on average, fragmenting files into micro-sections:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// ============================================================================
// Schemas & Types
// ============================================================================

...

// ============================================================================
// Constants
// ============================================================================
--- code end ---

This structural over-specification is a reliable AI-generated code signal. The banner density across 56 files totals 527 occurrences (averaging nearly 10 per file), indicating a systemwide pattern applied by code generation rather than intentional human choice.

Every adapter and major service exports an identically-structured 3-line factory function that simply calls `new ClassName(config)`:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
/**
 * Create GitHub adapter instance
 */
export function createGitHubAdapter(config: GitHubAdapterConfig): GitHubAdapter {
  return new GitHubAdapter(config);
}

/**
 * Create branch protection adapter instance
 */
export function createBranchProtectionAdapter(
  config: BranchProtectionConfig
): BranchProtectionAdapter {
  return new BranchProtectionAdapter(config);
}

/**
 * Create Linear adapter instance
 */
export function createLinearAdapter(config: LinearAdapterConfig): LinearAdapter {
  return new LinearAdapter(config);
}
--- code end ---

Same pattern appears in MetricsCollector, CostTracker, TraceManager, BranchProtectionAdapter, and more. None of these factories add any logic over the constructor. They carry JSDoc comments that restate the obvious. This is a by-the-book pattern applied uniformly by AI generation with no project-specific rationale.

GitHubAdapter, BranchProtectionAdapter, and LinearAdapter each log a 'Fetching X' message before every API call and a 'X fetched/created successfully' message after. This produces 2 log events per operation across 12+ methods with no added diagnostic value beyond what structured request logging (already handled by HttpClient) already captures:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
async getCommitStatuses(sha: string): Promise<CommitStatus[]> {
  this.logger.debug('Fetching commit statuses', { sha });
  try {
    ...
    this.logger.debug('Commit statuses fetched', { sha, count: response.data.length });
    return response.data;
  } catch (error) {
    this.logger.error('Failed to fetch commit statuses', { sha, error: serializeError(error) });
    throw this.normalizeError(error, 'getCommitStatuses');
  }
}
--- code end ---

This triple-log pattern (before, after-success, after-error) is repeated identically for getBranchProtection, getCheckRuns, getPullRequestReviews, compareCommits, createBranch, createPullRequest, getPullRequest, requestReviewers, getStatusChecks, mergePullRequest, enableAutoMerge, disableAutoMerge, triggerWorkflow, fetchIssue, fetchComments, updateIssue, postComment — approximately 20 methods across 3 adapters.

96 instances of `// Step N:` comments across 10 files create artificial procedural narration for sequential code that has no ambiguity:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// Step 1: Detect git repository root
const gitRoot = this.findGitRoot();
// Step 2: Check if already initialized
if (await this.handleAlreadyInitialized(configPath, flags, ctx)) {
// Step 3: Create directory structure (skip in dry-run)
if (!flags['dry-run']) {
// Step 4: Get repository URL for config
const repoUrl = this.getRepositoryUrl(gitRoot);
// Step 5: Create schema-backed configuration
const config = createDefaultConfig(repoUrl);
// Step 6: Write configuration (skip in dry-run)
// Step 7: Validate the created/computed configuration
--- code end ---

All 7 steps in init.ts are already named by their function calls and method names. The step numbers add nothing. Same pattern appears in specComposer.ts (17 instances), prdAuthoringEngine.ts (13 instances), branchManager.ts (12 instances), taskPlanner.ts (10 instances), and contextAggregator.ts (9 instances).

safeJson.ts has 105 comment lines out of 188 total (56%), the highest ratio in the codebase. The file's 4 utility functions each carry: a multi-line JSDoc summary, @param tags, @returns tag, and an extended @example block with console.log usage. The functions are trivial JSON.parse wrappers:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
/**
 * Safely parse JSON string with optional default value
 *
 * @param content - JSON string to parse
 * @param defaultValue - Optional default value if parsing fails
 * @returns Parsed value or default value
 *
 * @example
 * ```typescript
 * const data = safeJsonParse<User>(jsonString);
 * if (data) {
 *   console.log(data.name);
 * }
 *
 * // With default value
 * const config = safeJsonParse(jsonString, { enabled: false });
 * ```
 */
export function safeJsonParse<T>(content: string, defaultValue?: T): T | undefined {
  try {
    return JSON.parse(content) as T;
  } catch {
    return defaultValue;
  }
}
--- code end ---

The function body is 5 lines. The documentation block is 18 lines. The @example section shows usage that any TypeScript developer can infer from the signature.

writeActionQueueTypes.ts has 79 comment lines out of 166 total (48%). Every interface field carries a single-line JSDoc comment that restates the field name in plain English with no additional information:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
export interface WriteAction {
  /** Unique action ID */
  action_id: string;
  /** Action type */
  action_type: WriteActionType;
  /** GitHub provider identifier */
  provider: string;
  /** Repository owner */
  owner: string;
  /** Repository name */
  repo: string;
  /** Action payload */
  payload: WriteActionPayload;
  /** Idempotency key for deduplication */
  idempotency_key: string;
  /** Current status */
  status: WriteActionStatus;
  /** Number of retry attempts */
  retry_count: number;
  /** Maximum retry attempts */
  max_retries: number;
--- code end ---

Fields like `owner: string`, `repo: string`, `provider: string`, and `status: WriteActionStatus` need no documentation. The field names are fully self-explanatory. Same pattern appears in WriteActionQueueManifest, WriteActionQueueConfig, and QueueOperationResult.

httpTypes.ts (52% comment ratio) and branchProtection.ts (34 inline JSDoc annotations) apply per-field JSDoc uniformly to every interface field regardless of whether the field needs explanation:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// From httpTypes.ts:
export interface HttpClientConfig {
  /** Base URL for API requests */
  baseUrl: string;
  /** Provider type for rate limit tracking */
  provider: Provider;
  /** Authorization token (will be injected as Bearer token) */
  token?: string;
  /** Request timeout in milliseconds */
  timeout?: number;
  /** Maximum retry attempts */
  maxRetries?: number;
}

// From branchProtection.ts:
export interface RequiredStatusChecks {
  /** Whether status checks are enabled */
  enabled: boolean;
  /** Whether to require branches to be up to date before merging */
  strict: boolean;
  /** List of required status check contexts */
  contexts: string[];
}
--- code end ---

Fields like `baseUrl`, `timeout`, `maxRetries`, `enabled`, `strict`, and `contexts` are self-documenting. The JSDoc adds zero information beyond what TypeScript types already express.

13 instances across 11 files use an inline comment `// Ensure X directory exists` immediately before an `fs.mkdir` call with `{ recursive: true }`. The comment adds no information:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// Ensure status directory exists
await fs.mkdir(path.dirname(reportPath), { recursive: true });

// Ensure metrics directory exists
const metricsDir = path.dirname(this.metricsFilePath);
await fs.mkdir(metricsDir, { recursive: true });

// Ensure telemetry directory exists
const telemetryDir = path.dirname(this.costsFilePath);
await fs.mkdir(telemetryDir, { recursive: true });
--- code end ---

`fs.mkdir` with `{ recursive: true }` is idiomatically understood. Restating the intent in a comment is pure noise.

8 instances across 7 files use an inline comment `// Clean up temp file on error` or `// Atomic rename` immediately before boilerplate try/catch cleanup blocks:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
  } catch (error) {
    // Clean up temp file on error
    try {
      await fs.unlink(tempPath);
    } catch {
      // Ignore cleanup errors
    }
    throw error;
  }
--- code end ---

The atomic write-temp-then-rename pattern is a well-known idiom. The comment `// Clean up temp file on error` and `// Atomic rename` restate what the code plainly does. The pattern itself is duplicated identically in writeManifest (runDirectoryManager.ts), writeQueueManifest (queueStore.ts), saveApprovalsFile (approvalRegistry.ts), saveHashManifest, flush (metrics.ts), and queueSnapshotManager.

The write-temp-then-rename pattern is duplicated identically across at least 7 files: runDirectoryManager.ts (writeManifest), queueStore.ts (writeQueueManifest), approvalRegistry.ts (saveApprovalsFile), metrics.ts (flush), queueSnapshotManager.ts, validationRegistry.ts, and deployment/context.ts. Each implementation follows the identical structure:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
const tempPath = `${targetPath}.tmp.${crypto.randomBytes(8).toString('hex')}`;
try {
  const handle = await fs.open(tempPath, 'w');
  try {
    await handle.writeFile(content, 'utf-8');
    await handle.sync();
  } finally {
    await handle.close();
  }
  await fs.rename(tempPath, targetPath);
} catch (error) {
  try { await fs.unlink(tempPath); } catch { /* ignore */ }
  throw error;
}
--- code end ---

This is precisely the kind of boilerplate an AI generates in every file that needs disk writes, without extracting a shared utility.

contextRanking.ts contains inline comments that describe arithmetic that is self-evident from the variable names:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// Count path segments (slashes)
const depth = relativePath.split('/').length - 1;

// Normalize: depth 0 = 1.0, depth 5+ = 0.0
const maxDepth = 5;
const score = Math.max(0, 1 - depth / maxDepth);

// Calculate age in days
const ageMs = now.getTime() - gitLastModified.getTime();
const ageDays = ageMs / (1000 * 60 * 60 * 24);

// Empty files get lowest score
if (size === 0) {
  return 0.0;
}

// Optimal range: 1KB - 100KB
const optimalMin = 1024; // 1KB
const optimalMax = 100 * 1024; // 100KB
--- code end ---

Comments like `// Count path segments (slashes)`, `// Calculate age in days`, and `// Empty files get lowest score` describe operations that the variable names and values already communicate. The magic-number annotations (`// 1KB`, `// 100KB`) are genuinely useful and should be retained; the rest should be removed.

Three error classes — GitHubAdapterError, BranchProtectionError, LinearAdapterError — each have an identical 8-line constructor that only sets `this.name`:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
export class GitHubAdapterError extends AdapterError {
  constructor(
    message: string,
    errorType: ErrorType,
    statusCode?: number,
    requestId?: string,
    operation?: string
  ) {
    super(message, errorType, statusCode, requestId, operation);
    this.name = 'GitHubAdapterError';
  }
}
--- code end ---

All three classes are structurally identical — same signature, same super() call, only differing in `this.name` value. No class adds any behavior beyond the base class. This is a pure boilerplate multiplication pattern.

approvalRegistry.ts contains inline comments that narrate sequential operations with no non-obvious logic:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// Validate artifact hash matches current artifact
const approvalsData = await loadApprovalsFile(runDir, featureId);
...
// Create new approval record
const approvalId = `${gateType}-${randomUUID().split('-')[0]}`;
...
// Append approval record
await appendApprovalRecord(runDir, featureId, record);

// Update manifest inline (move from pending to completed, avoiding nested withLock deadlock)
const pending = manifest.approvals.pending.filter((a: string) => a !== gateType);
--- code end ---

Most of these comments restate the function call on the next line. The one exception is the `withLock` deadlock comment — that is a genuinely non-obvious constraint and should be kept.

LinearAdapter contains JSDoc on private helper methods that do 1-3 lines of work:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
/**
 * Format error message
 */
private formatError(error: unknown): string {
  if (error instanceof Error) {
    return error.message;
  }
  return String(error);
}

/**
 * Record request timestamp for sliding window tracking
 */
private recordRequest(timestamp: number): void {
  this.requestTimestamps.push(timestamp);
}

/**
 * Remove timestamps that are outside the sliding window
 */
private trimRequestWindow(now: number): void {
--- code end ---

Private methods called only from within the class do not benefit from JSDoc — they are implementation details. The method names already describe what they do.

branchProtectionReporter.ts and multiple other files contain `// File doesn't exist, create empty structure` or `// Validation registry not found or not readable` comments on ENOENT error branches that are already handled by the condition:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
  } catch (error) {
    if ((error as NodeJS.ErrnoException).code === 'ENOENT') {
      return null;
    }
    throw error;
  }

// From detectValidationMismatch:
  } catch (error) {
    // Validation registry not found or not readable
    if ((error as NodeJS.ErrnoException).code !== 'ENOENT') {
      throw error;
    }
  }
--- code end ---

The ENOENT code is self-documenting — it is the POSIX errno for 'No such file or directory'. Comments like 'File doesn't exist, create empty structure' add no information.

safeJson.ts includes @example code blocks that show console.log usage of functions whose behaviour is entirely described by the function signature and return type:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
/**
 * Safely parse JSON string with detailed result
 *
 * ...
 * @example
 * ```typescript
 * const result = safeJsonParseWithResult<Config>(jsonString);
 * if (result.success) {
 *   console.log(result.data);
 * } else {
 *   console.error('Parse failed:', result.error);
 * }
 * ```
 */
--- code end ---

The discriminated union `SafeJsonResult<T>` with `success: boolean` is self-documenting. The example adds no insight that the type definition does not already provide. Same issue on safeJsonParseValidated's @example block.
